    "patterns_used": [
      { "pattern": "Event-Driven Architecture (lightweight)", "rationale": "The 5-minute latency budget explicitly permits asynchronous processing. Decoupling delivery logic from notification logic prevents a Twilio outage from blocking delivery status updates. This is the #1 architectural reason to prefer Option B." },
      { "pattern": "Strategy Pattern (Channel Adapters)", "rationale": "New channels (push, WhatsApp) are added by implementing a ChannelAdapter interface. No modification to worker logic. Directly addresses the extensibility requirement." },
      { "pattern": "Competing Consumers", "rationale": "Multiple worker instances can consume from the same queue for horizontal scaling. Not needed day-one, but the architecture doesn't prevent it — free future optionality." },
      { "pattern": "Dead Letter Queue", "rationale": "Directly addresses the 'never silently drop' reliability requirement. Failed messages that exhaust retries land somewhere visible and replayable, not in /dev/null." },
      { "pattern": "Transactional Outbox (recommended)", "rationale": "Prevents the dual-write problem: delivery status saved to DB but event lost (or vice versa). Write event to an outbox table in the same DB transaction, then relay to queue. Critical for reliability guarantee. Can start with poll-based relay — simple for a small team." },
